editorialSummary.text: Mountain setting for a centuries-old, carved-stone Hindu temple devoted to Shiva & Shakti.

text.text:
It is said to be among one of the ancient temples, which was destroyed by Mughals (or some other muslim ruler). Currently the temple is under ASI (Archeological Survey of India). The temple still exists in half destroyed condition and you'll find damaged statues kept near the temple and also the Shikhara (Top of the temple) was destroyed. The statue of the deity inside the temple exists in damaged condition.
The temple is located on top of the mountain, so choose your mode of transport wisely. If you are visiting with your private vehicle, then the Temple's trust will charge you some 10-50rs, based on your vehicle.

text.text: One of the oldest living temple from North India. It's dedicated to Maa Mundeshwari Devi, believed to be a heaven for tantric tapasya back then. You can also see a centuries old Shivlinga and a beautiful Nandi adoring the centuries old temple. The temple closes from 12 to 12:30 PM for aarti. Wait time for darshan is 10 to 15 minutes on a Sunday. You will be mesmerised by the Nagara style architecture of the temple. There are 528 steps to the temple but a road directly reached the base of the temple. Around the temple, you will see thousand years old ruins from the temple. Kindly do not sit on those ruins as they are a rich heritage of our country.

text.text: This temple of Maa Mundeshwari is on the peak of Panvara mountain in Kaimur district. This temple was built during the Gupta period. This is the oldest functioning temple of India, that is, worship has always been happening in it without any stop. There is a pentagonal Shiva Linga in this temple. Apart from this, there are also idols of other gods and goddesses. The temple is octagonal. There is beautiful carving on it. To reach the temple, stairs have been made for pedestrians and a path for vehicles to reach the top. The idols are scattered in the temple premises.
Ruiya Gram Panchayat
